<div class="bl">

  <h2>Everyone Gets This Part Wrong</h2>

  <p>The standard advice goes like this: quit smoking, and your body takes care of the rest. You’ll find that claim repeated on every health website on the internet. It’s the reason people expect to feel better within months of quitting.</p>

  <p><strong>It’s also incomplete to the point of being misleading.</strong></p>

  <div class="bl-stat">
    <div class="bl-stat-num">1 in 2</div>
    <div class="bl-stat-label">long-term smokers still had persistent respiratory symptoms&nbsp;—&nbsp;shortness of breath, daily cough, phlegm&nbsp;—&nbsp;despite normal breathing tests</div>
    <div class="bl-stat-src">—&nbsp;SPIROMICS study, published in JAMA, August 2023</div>
  </div>

  <p>Here’s what’s actually happening. When you quit, your body stops absorbing new tar, particulates, and oxidative compounds. Good. But the stuff that’s already in there&nbsp;—&nbsp;the mucus buildup coating your bronchial walls, the inflammatory residue sitting in your tissue, the oxidative damage to your alveoli&nbsp;—&nbsp;<strong>that doesn’t pack a bag and leave.</strong></p>

  <p>Think of it this way: your lungs are a fish tank that hasn’t been cleaned in 15 years. You can stop dumping food in. But the water’s still murky, the filter’s clogged, and the gravel at the bottom is packed with sludge. <strong>Stopping the input doesn’t fix the tank. Someone still has to scrub it.</strong></p>

  <p>That’s the gap. And it’s the reason a 58-year-old who quit a decade ago still can’t keep up with her grandkids at the park.</p>

