    <p>“I quit twelve years ago and still couldn’t take a full breath. My doctor said this was ‘just how it is now.’&nbsp;I didn’t buy it.”</p>
    <div class="bl-attr">—&nbsp;Rob S., 52, 31 years smoking</div>
  </div>

  <h2>Why Everything at the Pharmacy Misses the Point</h2>

  <p>If you’ve gone looking for answers, you already know how this goes. The pharmacy has an entire aisle of options, and none of them were designed for your situation.</p>

  <p><strong>Cough suppressants</strong> tell your brain to stop coughing. They don’t clear the congestion that’s triggering the cough. That’s like unplugging a smoke detector and calling it fire prevention.</p>

  <p><strong>Decongestants</strong> shrink swollen nasal passages. Useful for a head cold. Useless for residual buildup deep in your bronchial tree&nbsp;—&nbsp;which is where the problem actually lives after years of exposure.</p>

  <p><strong>Generic “lung health”&nbsp;supplements</strong> throw a handful of vitamins at the wall and hope something sticks. Most contain ingredients studied for immune function, not respiratory clearance. There’s a difference, and it’s not small.</p>

